nction, as Angel's protector, Father Alexis, puts it, "between the authority of faith and the application of this authority in the hands of men." As translator Patricia J. F. Worth argues in her introduction, the novel's emphasis on freedom of inquiry, benevolence, and moral reform inspired other nineteenth-century writers, including Fyodor Dostoyevsky, Matthew Arnold, and Henry James, and the novel is also relevant to twenty-first-century discussions of religious authority and rigid adherence to doctrine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGhost stories. 0aMonastic and religious lifevFiction. 0aMonastic and religious lifexFiction. 0aMonksvFiction. 0aMonksxFiction. 4aArea Studies : French Studies. 4aGeneral Interest : Fiction. 4aLiterature : Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aSand, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWorth, Patricia J. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845626340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438456263423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438456263/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles